I don&#39;t think there is a built-in function for it. But you can simply do the following;

    db.collection.aggregate([
      {
        $unwind: &quot;$coordinates&quot;
      },
      {
        $unwind: &quot;$coordinates&quot;
      },
      {
        $group: {
          _id: null,
          minX: {
            $min: { $arrayElemAt: [ &quot;$coordinates&quot;, 0 ] }
          },
          maxX: {
            $max: { $arrayElemAt: [ &quot;$coordinates&quot;, 0 ] }
          },
          minY: {
            $min: { $arrayElemAt: [ &quot;$coordinates&quot;, 1 ] }
          },
          maxY: {
            $max: { $arrayElemAt: [ &quot;$coordinates&quot;, 1 ] }
          }
        }
      }
    ])

Where first unwraps the `coordinates` array with [`$unwind`][1] (twice for extra `[ ]` block), so that `aggregate pipeline` can iterate on it. Then we just use a [`$group`][2] with `_id: null` which is [a special operation][3] to evaluate min/max values for all elements of the array.

which will get you a response you request;

    [
      {
        &quot;_id&quot;: null,
        &quot;maxX&quot;: 47.7803203666229,
        &quot;maxY&quot;: 52.0987759993153,
        &quot;minX&quot;: 25.5377574370701,
        &quot;minY&quot;: 42.8545750237221
      }
    ]

check on [mongoplayground][4]


  [1]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/unwind/
  [2]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/group/
  [3]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/group/#group-by-null
  [4]: https://mongoplayground.net/p/kbvCiV778dL

The most efficient way is to employ the [`$map`][1] and [`$reduce`][2] operators along with [`$let`][3]. This allows you to process each document by manipulating the array&#39;s *inline* and then use [`$min`][4] and [`$max`][5] operators to obtain the bounding values:

    db.collection.aggregate([
      { &quot;$replaceRoot&quot;: {  
        &quot;newRoot&quot;: {
          &quot;$let&quot;: {
            &quot;vars&quot;: {
              &quot;m&quot;: {
                &quot;$map&quot;: {
                  &quot;input&quot;: {
                    &quot;$reduce&quot;: {
                      &quot;input&quot;: &quot;$coord.coordinates&quot;,
                      &quot;initialValue&quot;: [],
                      &quot;in&quot;: {
                        &quot;$concatArrays&quot;: [ &quot;$$value&quot;, &quot;$$this&quot;]
                      }
                    }
                  },
                  &quot;in&quot;: {
                    &quot;x&quot;: { &quot;$arrayElemAt&quot;: [ &quot;$$this&quot;, 0 ] },
                    &quot;y&quot;: { &quot;$arrayElemAt&quot;: [ &quot;$$this&quot;, 1 ] }
                  }
                }
              }
            },
            &quot;in&quot;: {
              &quot;_id&quot;: &quot;$_id&quot;,
              &quot;coord&quot;: &quot;$coord&quot;,
              &quot;minX&quot;: { &quot;$min&quot;: &quot;$$m.x&quot; },
              &quot;minY&quot;: { &quot;$min&quot;: &quot;$$m.y&quot; },
              &quot;maxX&quot;: { &quot;$max&quot;: &quot;$$m.x&quot; },
              &quot;maxY&quot;: { &quot;$max&quot;: &quot;$$m.y&quot; }
            }
          }
        }
      }}
    ])

And the output, would be like:

    {
            &quot;_id&quot; : ObjectId(&quot;5d9330e95994eb7018f59218&quot;),
            &quot;coord&quot; : {
                    &quot;type&quot; : &quot;Polygon&quot;,
                    &quot;coordinates&quot; : [
                            [
                                    [
                                            25.5377574375611,
                                            42.8545750237221
                                    ],
                                    [
                                            47.7803203666229,
                                            42.8545750237221
                                    ],
                                    [
                                            47.7803203661319,
                                            52.0987759993153
                                    ],
                                    [
                                            25.5377574370701,
                                            52.0987759993153
                                    ],
                                    [
                                            25.5377574375611,
                                            42.8545750237221
                                    ]
                            ]
                    ]
            },
            &quot;minX&quot; : 25.5377574370701,
            &quot;minY&quot; : 42.8545750237221,
            &quot;maxX&quot; : 47.7803203666229,
            &quot;maxY&quot; : 52.0987759993153
    }

Note the usage of the [`$replaceRoot`][6] aggregation pipeline stage, as this will allow the nested expressions with [`$let`][3] to essentially provide *global variables* to the document to produce that can be utilized in any output property.

The [`$reduce`][2] here basically serves the function to *flatten* the array from the standard GeoJSON form into just an array of coordinate pairs, without the additional bounding array.

This then feeds input to the [`$map`][1] which employs [`$arrayElemAt`][7] in order to *re-map* each coordinate pair into an *object* with `x` and `y` keys. This makes things much more simple for the actual execution or *output* section of the [`$let`][3].

&gt; **Note**: An alternate approach to using [`$arrayElemAt`][7] against each key within the [`$map`][1] might well be to use [`$zip`][8] and [`$arrayToObject`][9]:

&gt;             
       &quot;in&quot;: {
            &quot;$arrayToObject&quot;: { &quot;$zip&quot;: { &quot;inputs&quot;: [ [&quot;x&quot;,&quot;y&quot;], &quot;$$this&quot; ] } }
       }

&gt; It has the same principle in the overall output, but takes advantage of [`$zip`][8] producing &quot;paired&quot; arrays, which also happens to be valid input for [`$arrayToObject`][9] to produce the final *object* form.


In the final part, we now basically have an *array of objects* with the named keys `x` and `y`. MongoDB allows a convenient way to *remap* simply the values for those named keys with notation like `&quot;$$m.x&quot;` where the `&quot;$$m` expression related to the named variable of the [`$let`][3] and is our *array of objects*, and the `.x` part of course simply means ***only the values of `x`***. This is a basic shorthand for a [`$map`][1] statement in itself, which suits this special usage case.

These arrays of values for specific properties can now be applied to the [`$min`][4] and [`$max`][5] operators, and this is how you get you `min` and `max` coordinates for a bounding rectangle.

---

**Note that *inline operators* for arrays should always be preferred to [`$unwind`][10].**

The [`$unwind`][10] aggregation pipeline stage was an old introductory way of dealing with array elements by essentially *flattening* them into separate documents.

Though necessary when you actually want to *group* on a value as a key that comes from within an array, most operations which don&#39;t actually need that ( like this one ) can be done with more modern approaches.

The usage of [`$unwind`][10] is actually a **huge** performance penalty, due to it&#39;s function essentially being to replicate the entire parent document content of the field containing the array into it&#39;s own new document. Particularly in large datasets this has a very negative effect on performance, due to much increases I/O and memory usage.

The main lesson being, unless it&#39;s necessary to the operation being performed ( and here it is not ) then you should not be using [`$unwind`][10] in an aggregation pipeline. It might *look* easier to understand, but your code is actually hurting the system it&#39;s running on by including it.

---

Alternate Client Approach
---

Note also that if you don&#39;t actually need these results for any *further* aggregation processing, then it&#39;s probably a lot cleaner to code in the client as each document is processed.

For example, here&#39;s a plain JavaScript version for the shell:

    db.collection.find().map(({ _id, coord }) =&gt;
      (({ coordinates }) =&gt;
        ({
          _id,
          coord,
          ...(m =&gt; 
            ({
              minX: Math.min(...m.map(({ x }) =&gt; x)),
              minY: Math.min(...m.map(({ y }) =&gt; y)),
              maxX: Math.max(...m.map(({ x }) =&gt; x)),
              maxY: Math.max(...m.map(({ y }) =&gt; y))
            })
          )(
            ((c) =&gt; c.reduce((o,e) =&gt; [ ...o, ...e ],[]).map(([x,y]) =&gt; ({ x, y })) )(coordinates)
          )
      })
      )(coord)
    )

That has exactly the same output and is not nearly as unwieldy as the BSON operator statements required for an aggregation pipeline.


  [1]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/map/
  [2]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/reduce/
  [3]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/let/
  [4]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/min/
  [5]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/max/
  [6]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/replaceRoot/
  [7]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/arrayElemAt/
  [8]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/zip/
  [9]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/arrayToObject/
  [10]: https://docs.mongodb.com/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/unwind/

